  </p>
  <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1"/>
  <p>
   <br/>
   If you do this sign with just one movement it tends to function more as a 
	verb and can mean "influence" or "affect" or the verb "advise."
   <br/>
   <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/-sk9mV0Jwfk?rel=0" width="560">
   </iframe>
  </p>
  <p>
   <img border="0" height="209" src="/images/advise-counsel1.jpg" width="203"/>
   <img border="0" height="209" src="/images/advise-counsel2.jpg" width="203"/>
   <img border="0" height="209" src="/images/advise-counsel3.jpg" width="203"/>
  </p>
  <p>
  </p>
  <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1" width="50%"/>
  <p>
   <br/>
   Notes:
  </p>
  <p>
   The COUNSEL/advice sign can use either a single or a double movement.
   <br/>
   It will generally use a double movement when used as a noun or a repeated 
	process (advis
   <b>
    <i>
     ing
    </i>
   </b>
   ).
  </p>
  <p>
   However, in context a single movement of this sign can still be a 
			noun. (For example: "MY ADVICE? YOU SHOULD..."
   <br/>
   <br/>
   You can put a "person / agent"
  marker on the sign and it will mean "counselor" or
  "advisor."
  </p>
